vBVthxp35Z6Z9fMFenPbKLN_vDVEyZ_RzOfZHtyNNWWLLjAthbKONa3W-W-x2NXMacSYPFvOIWcZC5E0PMU8mdPe-g_MJioon-YrFj-Uq8W9PHGsXPkJjceGu_jYk5-n2pHQGfAfYrJ_kyd_7WTiMTg7n9OMsX94GWmAQ6d2mqYiHAGibzm2RDyTvEe86xDzsU70GEY1LdyUZhQRwt3UHdOaZOhLmsXx3q8ntBlSPcTd3TaubhzsnyqH9yyXAGl9jI67oXaGW4rPCbmdPIhU_Aomfn9OuG8biRRPGR3Zy3yIFC1IFCmjmA4kI3mZy8SSXxtWmNJNpnroEhztnG4-65x2uPAan-27w1xgOycqtb894P3kzzj_vyQvVaDnt36NEqfAZIQPUl9DXNjipurHykubvJd_PcvtvqTniI4oKrO2SQgDmfVznr2O08ZmHRNnge67oPI4Jb3cKl4dT_lzUPJ07nukaK3aVt8MslcyaBhFIRMLO5PP-iUs-wglZgx9yeXIVeSoxMZMOLYMfuxX4xoAH1qUFir4JSftzeovDY5Wrgu_oQsuZwBquQ4Q5_-3-j9DR23ylg7RwUtDno37pPhMyugpfQaoYyg2o6STjO4v8TVgRpPnn0HeRvKq0e9Bl3M6-2YJ1ou9x01_hWWfRDh15xuanRsj-OMQ6xKB2ynWyA2izM6jGcEddIy-6CfbypEpxfUCMOgwYOwp1hScAsFOZQO-tV75t99Y2LZVoSME8j-NgNe1wDyWEDGLMNMKgWHBvrR1\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Spock and JUnit setup**\\n\\nI’m considering the structure where top-level classes don't extend Specification, but nested ones do. The Spock AST transform should cover these nested classes. Interesting point about public nested classes — JUnitCore can run them, and I wonder about Groovy's default public modifier. The developer mentions avoiding `$` in class names, which is a solid point. I’m also pondering if Spock 1.0 supports static nested specs. It looks like I’ll need to check the run count for unrolled iterations too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying run counts in Spock 1.0**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out how Spock 1.0 counts data-driven iterations. It seems like they probably count individually, but maybe if they’re not unrolled, the entire feature counts as one? With `@Unroll`, it looks like `runCount` equals the number of iterations, but I'm a bit uncertain on that. I wonder if I should avoid specifying an exact run count and just use `>=`. I could assert whether the events list includes the expected behavior.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Working on JUnit setup**\\n\\nI need a comprehensive setup, which might require annotations and extensions. There’s a potential issue with the top-level public class due to underscores in the file path and class name in the existing package. I think JUnit Jupiter can coexist with JUnit 4, so I’ll use JUnitCore and the Result class. I also need to create a directory if it already exists and decide whether to write or edit files.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_F0TRsPGvL7x79SDXQl3YFAQv|fc_0e46dba2252049be016a022b88aef8819d87df3b399208469e", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.spockframework/spock-core/1.0-groovy-2.4/src/test/groovy/org_spockframework/spock_core/Spock_coreTest.groovy", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_spockframework.spock_core\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\nimport org.junit.runner.JUnitCore\nimport org.junit.runner.Result\nimport spock.lang.AutoCleanup\nimport spock.lang.Issue\nimport spock.lang.Narrative\nimport spock.lang.See\nimport spock.lang.Shared\nimport spock.lang.Specification\nimport spock.lang.Stepwise\nimport spock.lang.Subject\nimport spock.lang.Title\nimport spock.lang.Unroll\nimport spock.util.concurrent.AsyncConditions\nimport spock.util.concurrent.BlockingVariable\nimport spock.util.concurrent.PollingConditions\nimport spock.util.environment.RestoreSystemProperties\n\nimport java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService\nimport java.util.concurrent.Executors\nimport java.util.concurrent.Future\nimport java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit\nimport java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat\n\npublic class Spock_coreTest {\n    private static final String RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY = 'spock.core.tck.restore.property'\n\n    @Test\n    void executesSpecificationLifecycleDataTablesAndExceptionConditions() {\n        LifecycleSpecification.events.clear()\n\n        Result result = JUnitCore.runClasses(LifecycleSpecification)\n\n        assertThat(result.failures).isEmpty()\n        assertThat(result.runCount).isGreaterThanOrEqualTo(3)\n        assertThat(LifecycleSpecification.events).containsSubsequence(\n                'setupSpec',\n                'setup',\n                'data:3',\n                'cleanup',\n                'setup',\n                'data:4',\n                'cleanup',\n                'setup',\n                'thrown:invalid input',\n                'no-exception:SPOCK',\n                'cleanup',\n                'cleanupSpec')\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void invokesBuiltinExtensionsForAutoCleanupAndSystemPropertyRestoration() {\n        AutoCleanupSpecification.events.clear()\n        String previousValue = System.getProperty(RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY)\n        System.setProperty(RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY, 'original')\n\n        try {\n            Result cleanupResult = JUnitCore.runClasses(AutoCleanupSpecification)\n            Result propertyResult = JUnitCore.runClasses(SystemPropertySpecification)\n\n            assertThat(cleanupResult.failures).isEmpty()\n            assertThat(propertyResult.failures).isEmpty()\n            assertThat(AutoCleanupSpecification.events).containsExactly('feature-body', 'dispose')\n            assertThat(System.getProperty(RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY)).isEqualTo('original')\n        } finally {\n            if (previousValue == null) {\n                System.clearProperty(RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY)\n            } else {\n                System.setProperty(RESTORE_PROPERTY_KEY, previousValue)\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void honorsStepwiseExecutionAndDocumentationAnnotations() {\n        AnnotatedStepwiseSpecification.events.clear()\n\n        Result result = JUnitCore.runClasses(AnnotatedStepwiseSpecification)\n\n        assertThat(result.failures).isEmpty()\n        assertThat(AnnotatedStepwiseSpecification.events).containsExact